social_posts.post_text: This is something that’s been brewing for a while and I’m excited to start sharing my new journey with everyone! After nearly a decade of aquarium/water feature maintenance and design in various avenues I have broken off and started my own company. My intent is to share as much about my journey starting this business as I can through social media and YouTube content. I’m very grateful for the jump start I’ve had already and thankful for all the help that’s got me to this point. I’m stockpiling content and lining up new projects as we speak! Join me on this new venture and help me by sharing. Welcome to Afishionados Aquarium Design (LLC)

My @innovative.marine SR80 has been through some changes lately, and still changing. I lost a lot of SPS colonies a few months ago due to a lot of reasons 😂 most of them having to do with me and my time/commitment to being able to keep up with the needs of said corals. So here we are and actually much happier. More soft corals, more movement, more character, more liveliness. There is something to be said about a mixed reef that is predominantly soft coral. They are extremely underrated for one. As much as you think you like the psychedelic rainbow effect, deep down you really just want a natural looking mixed reef. There’s a thousand way to do it but soft corals are the way to go. Your creativity is being suppressed by the illusion of cough syrup dream corals and collectoritis, don’t give in! Give soft corals a chance, some of them are surprisingly beautiful. Obviously this all subjective and I’m just sharing my opinion. Please create the aquarium that pleases you most. If you’re happy then more than likely you are going to take better care of what’s in the aquarium. In reality that’s the most important part.

Excited to show y’all more of this recent redesign that I did! This was shortly after completion and I haven’t seen it yet looking crystal clear, can’t wait to get some good shots of it then. This is a slow growing, epiphytic, layout. All of the plants are attached to forest black wood and suspended above an open sand bottom with river stone accent. There’s also a ton of hides and caves on the bottom and on the wood for some special Plecos! This layout was designed to accommodate some medium/large (and growing) Clown Loaches but the other fish include: Endlers, Gourami, and Siamese Algae Eaters.

So what goes into an aquarium design? Well, a lot. Gathering materials and tools, planning each step, accepting that it won’t go exactly as planned - building a cohesive layout before it’s actually built. When it comes right down to it though, it takes a lot of effort and meticulous, delicate movement. It is tiring! It’s important to treat each movement with respect for the next and appreciation for the last. It will go smoothly if you trust yourself and trust your materials to find their way into a layout.
It’s not perfect but it’s healthy - my new motto for this aquarium

I finally got a new partner for my 8+ year old Ocellaris Clownfish! She used to have a partner.. they were actually together for a few years. I’m not sure what happened, but one day I checked on the tank to find the male had died. This female can be a little aggressive to the other fish and especially my hand ✋🏻 when I put it into the tank. I’m taking the safe route and keeping her new partner in a clear breeder box so they can get used to each other without the risk of injury - useful dating advice I learned from my own experiences 😂

I was going to wait a little bit longer to introduce the new clownfish but I observed two things: 1) my older clownfish was approaching the box and investigating all around without showing any signs of aggression or posturing. 2) the new clownfish seemed a little sluggish and wasn’t eating well in the breeder box. So I decided to release it into the tank ahead of schedule and I definitely made the right choice. After one night together they are all over each other and the new fish is eating like a pig! I’m still hopeful that when the posturing begins that the female will accept the male. I’ll be ready if things get out of hand.

Wait! Before you ask.. They are Red Mangrove trees. They are not very difficult to keep. It is a saltwater tank. The tank is a @innovative.marine 25gallon. The lights are par38 LED’s. The light fixture is called a “tree lamp”. The trees are about 8.5 years old. The Clownfishes are very cute. The Nemo is Emo. (The last two weren’t answers to FAQ’s, they are just facts) Am I missing anything? 😂
Living Room Lagoon 🌊 🏝️
SO DRAMATIC 💅🏻

The trees can live in saltwater because they are able to essentially “sweat” the salt out of their vascular systems. If you don’t rinse the salt off it can dry and damage areas of the trees. They rely on tropical rainfall to survive. So I emulate the rainfall in my living room by spraying them with freshwater every few weeks.

Don’t tell me I can’t keep my corals clean and white! 😂 Anyway, I changed a few things in my @ultumnaturesystems 45A. Had to remove the pink dottyback and yellow clown goby due to aggression issues. There’s some new red hermits, a Trapezia crab, and a group of Biota Upside down Gobies (Trimma striatum) that I’ve really taken a liking to. I want to add more of them! This tank has been an evolving situation, like every aquarium, but I think I’m on a path that can last. The macroalgae has gotten bumped off the corals and is just chillin in the back section. Probably going to pull that out. I think I like the clean white look the most Current tankmates also include a Two Spot Goby, Zanzibar banded shrimp and the Black Clown Goby that takes front and center. Simple, filter-less, shrimp tank! Most of my shelf aquariums are powered only by light. This is by far the easiest type of aquarium to keep. If you’re one of those that thinks aquariums are difficult I’d tell you to try one of these.

Ten Tank Commandments:

1. Nothing good happens quickly 
2. Dilution is the solution 
3. Waste in, waste out
4. Plant Heavily 
5. Feed and Fertilize 
6. Clean the glass in front of substrate 
7. Trim often 
8. Less fish is better 
9. Try something new 
10. Be yourself

What’s the longest you’ve ever had the same aquarium/aquascape going? Let me know in the comments! For me, it’s this one and I’ve had it going for around 8 years. (The trees are older, around 9) My keys to success are very simple. The setup is most important. Setup your aquarium to care for and maintain something that you know you’ll have time for, even when times are tough! Simple is better. Next: Consistency is king. Keep up with routine care and you’ll almost never encounter an issue that won’t resolve with time and patience. That is all! Aquariums are as easy or as difficult as you want to make them.
